<bioghist altrender="biography" encodinganalog="545" id="a2">
<head>Biographical Note</head>
<p>
George McKenzie Roberts was born on December 28, 1886 at Vergennes, Vermont to George Simon and Florence Louise (McKenzie) Roberts. He married twice, to Anne Edith Campbell on October 20, 1909 at New Haven, and to Grace Agnes (Rhodes) Perkins on November 22, 1943 at Reno. It is believed that both marriages ended in divorce. There were no children. Roberts died on April 7, 1980 at San Francisco, California.
</p>
<p>
Roberts was educated only to the eighth or ninth grade. He began employment with General Electric in 1901. From 1919 to 1953 he worked for the International General Electric Company, Inc. in New York City as Credit Manager, Assistant Treasurer, and Treasurer. He was also Treasurer and a Director of Electrical Export Corporation. He was Chief of the Foreign Trade Branch, U.S. Office of Price Stabilization, Washington, D.C. from 1951 until his retirement in 1953. He was a director of the New York Board of Trade and of other business clubs and associations from 1920 to 1950.
</p>
<p>
Although Roberts did not publish any books, he published two genealogies that ran serially in the <emph render="italic">New York Genealogical and Biographical Record</emph>: "The Druse Genealogy," in 1938-1939, and "The Denslow Family in America," from 1946-1950 and 1957-1959. He produced a series of vital records, cemetery records, land and tax records, probate records, census enumerations, and Revolutionary soldiers' records, all relating to the town of Enfield, New Hampshire, in the <emph render="italic">N.Y.G. &amp; B. Record</emph> in 1957. He also published and article, "On the Marring of Research Sources," in <emph render="italic">The American Genealogist</emph> in October 1955. He published his Ancestor Table in that same issue.
</p>
<p>
Roberts was elected a Fellow of The American Society of Genealogists in 1950. He also belonged to the New England Historic Genealogical Society, the New York Genealogical and Biographical Society, the S.A. R., for which he served as Treasurer General and Genealogist General, Society of Colonial Wars in the State of New York, New York State Historical Association, Vermont, New Hampshire and Connecticut Historical Societies, Descendants of the Illegitimate Sons and Daughters of the Kings of Britain, Denslow Family Association, and others.
</p>
<p>
Source: <emph render="italic">Newsletter of the American Society of Genealogists</emph> 39.1 (January 1981): 3-4.
</p>

</bioghist>


<scopecontent encodinganalog="520" id="a3">
	<head>Scope and Content</head>
	<p>These papers contain manuscript drafts of the following genealogies: <emph render="italic">John Roberts, 1751-1834, of Hartford, Conn. : his family and descendants</emph>; <emph render="italic">Andrew Smith, 1779-1819 of Hartford, Conn. : his family and descendants</emph>; <emph render="italic">Ebenezer Spear, 1762-1826 of Hartford, Conn. : his family and descendants</emph>; and <emph render="italic">Abel, 1789-1875 &amp; Elizabeth (Spear), 1793-1875, Wellington of Bethel, Vermont : their family and descendants</emph>. The Roberts and Smith genealogies are accompanied by correspondence and other material accumulated by Roberts while gathering genealogical data. These files are arranged by correspondent. 
Also present are genealogical records about the Roberts, Smith and Spear Families divided into cemetery, estate, and vital records. These files contain some photocopies of original estate papers, and death and marriage certificates. Finally, there are a few notecards relating to the Denslow genealogy, but there are no other papers related to that project.
</p>
</scopecontent>

